/tr><tr><td>Mean (average)</td><td style=\"text-align: center;\">100</td></tr><tr><td>Hgb A1c</td><td style=\"text-align: center;\">â‰¤6%</td></tr></tbody></table>'),(310,221,'section_two_label','q visit'),(311,221,'sectiontwo','<h3>Subsequent OB Visits</h3><ul><li>Visits every 2 weeks in the first and second trimester to evaluate blood sugars. More frequent evaluation may be necessary in those with poor control or requiring multiple insulin adjustments.</li><li>Weekly visits after 28-30 weeks.</li><li>Targeted ultrasound at 18-20 weeks.</li><li>Fetal echocardiogram at 22-24 weeks.</li><li>Ultrasound for fluid and growth approximately every 4 weeks starting at 24-28 weeks.</li><li>Hgb A1c each trimester.</li><li>Antenatal fetal testing every week beginning at 32 weeks with NST, BPP, modified BPP or CST. Patients with IUGR, hypertension, diabetic vasculopathy or history of IUFD may warrent earlier and more frequent testing.</li></ul>'),(312,221,'section_three_label','Del'),(313,221,'sectionthree','<h3>Delivery</h3><ul><li>Schedule for delivery between 39-40 weeks with reassuring testing.</li><li>Ultrasound for fetal growth within 3 weeks of delivery.</li><li>Recommend elective cesarean for estimated fetal weight â‰¥ 4200-4500 grams</li><li>Assess glycemic control. If there is evidence of poor glucose control, maternal vasculopathy or nephropathy (White\'s â‰¥ D) then consider amniocentesis bewteen 36-38 weeks for fetal lung maturity studies with delivery if mature.</li></ul>'),(314,221,'section_four_label','Insulin'),(315,221,'sectionfour','<p><strong>Total Insulin Doseâ€ :</strong></p><ul><li><p><strong>1st Trimester: 0.6-0.8 U/Kg*</strong></p></li></ul><ul><li><p><strong>2nd Trimester: 1.0 U/Kg</strong></p></li></ul><ul><li><p><strong>3rd Trimester: 1.2 U/Kg</strong></p></li></ul><p><strong>Insulin is divided into 1/2 long acting and 1/2 short acting:</strong></p><table border=\"0\"><tbody><tr><td>Â </td><td><strong>Insulin</strong></td><td><strong>Administer</strong></td></tr><tr><td><strong>1/2 long acting</strong></td><td><strong>Preferred</strong>: Glargine</td><td>Once a day, same timeâ€¡</td></tr><tr><td>Â </td><td><strong>Alternative</strong>: NPH</td><td>2/3 in AM and 1/3 at bedtimeÂ§</td></tr><tr><td><strong>1/2 short acting</strong></td><td><strong>Preferred</strong>: Lispro/Aspart</td><td>1/3 prior to breakfast, lunch, and dinner</td></tr></tbody></table><p>&nbsp;</p><p>*Type 1 diabetics generally need a lower insulin dose (0.6 units/kg) than Type 2 diabetics (0.8-1.0 units/kg).Â  The majority of Type 1 diabetics will be on insulin prior to pregnancy; their insulin dosing should be determined by prior requirements and current control.<br />â€  For insulin naÃ¯ve subjects, consideration may be given to reducing the starting dose by 25% with aggressive titration up after 3-7 days of blood glucose monitoring.<br />â€¡ The maximum dose of insulin glargine that should be administered in one injection is 70 units.Â  If a patient requires more than 70 units of insulin glargine, administer as BID dosing.<br />Â§ The evening dose of NPH may be administered at dinner to reduce the number of injections; however this strategy is associated with an increased frequency of night-time hypoglycemia.</p>'),(469,316,'_wp_attached_file','2013/07/APEC_install_img006.jpeg'),(470,316,'_wp_attachment_metadata','a:5:{s:5:\"width\";i:368;s:6:\"height\";i:716;s:4:\"file\";s:32:\"2013/07/APEC_install_img006.jpeg\";s:5:\"sizes\";a:8:{s:9:\"thumbnail\";a:4:{s:4:\"file\";s:32:\"APEC_install_img006-150x150.jpeg\";s:5:\"width\";i:150;s:6:\"height\";i:150;s:9:\"mime-type\";s:10:\"image/jpeg\";}s:6:\"medium\";a:4:{s:4:\"file\";s:32:\"APEC_install_img006-154x300.jpeg\";s:5:\"width\";i:154;s:6:\"height\";i:300;s:9:\"mime-type\";s:10:\"image/jpeg\";}s:13:\"wpbs-featured\";a:4:{s:4:\"file\";s:32:\"APEC_install_img006-368x300.jpeg\";s:5:\"width\";i:368;s:6:\"height\";i:300;s:9:\"mime-type\";s:10:\"image/jpeg\";}s:18:\"wpbs-featured-home\";a:4:{s:4:\"file