Adjust'),(393,234,'sectionfour','<h3>Adjustment to Insulin</h3><ul><li>Adjustments to long-acting insulin glargine should not be made more frequently than every 48 hours.</li><li>Adjust insulin when &gt;50% of blood sugars are greater than target (FBS &gt;95 mg/dL, 1-hour postprandial &gt;140mg/dL, 2-hour postprandial &gt;120mg/dL).</li><li>Adjustments to long-acting insulin will correct fasting blood sugars.</li><li>Adjustments to pre-meal short acting insulin will correct the postprandial blood sugar for that meal.</li><li>Increases to insulin can be made in increments of 10%. For patients in the inpatient setting, more aggressive dose-adjustment can be performed in the face of marked hyperglycemia.</li></ul><h3>Â </h3><h3>Safety &amp; Counseling</h3><ul><li>Fast-acting insulin should not be injected unless the patient is planning to eat immediately.</li><li>Any patient on insulin should receive a prescription for a glucagon kit. At least one family member or housemate should be instructed on how and when to administer glucagon.</li></ul>'),(394,234,'section_five_label',''),(395,234,'sectionfive',''),(396,235,'_wp_attached_file','2013/06/APEC-GDM-guideline-11.pdf'),(544,418,'_edit_last','3'),(545,418,'_edit_lock','1383863173:3'),(556,418,'section_five_label',''),(557,418,'sectionfive',''),(558,418,'version','07/31/2013'),(559,419,'_edit_last','5'),(560,419,'_edit_lock','1390428348:5'),(561,419,'_wp_page_template','default'),(647,742,'_edit_lock','1390403283:3'),(648,742,'_edit_last','4'),(649,743,'_wp_attached_file','2014/01/APEC-TWIN-guideline-1.pdf'),(650,744,'_wp_attached_file','2014/01/APEC-TWIN-guideline-11.pdf'),(651,742,'narrative_pdf','744'),(652,742,'narrative','<p>Â Â Â  Twin pregnancies have increased 65% since 1980 as a result of advanced maternal age, the enhanced use of ovulation induction agents, and assisted reproductive technology.Â  Multifetal pregnancies are at higher risk of maternal and fetal complications with perinatal morbidity and mortality rates 3-4 times greater than in singleton pregnancies. (ACOG, 2004 reaffirmed 2009)The increased morbidity and mortality rates are associated with pregnancy complications including gestational diabetes, preeclampsia, preterm labor, preterm PROM, placental abruption, pyelonephritis, preterm delivery, intrauterine growth restriction (IUGR), postpartum hemorrhage, congenital anomalies, and cerebral palsy. To minimize risks, patients with multiples require close monitoring and frequent follow up.(ACOG, 2004 reaffirmed 2009)</p><h4>Pathophysiology</h4><p>Â Â Â  Twin gestations can be monozygotic, a single fertilized ovum that splits into 2 fetuses or dizygotic, two separate fertilized ova.Â  In the US, two-thirds of twins are dizygotic and one-third monozygotic. (Cunningham et al., 2010)Dizygotic pregnancies are genetically dissimilar, dichorionic diamniotic, and are associated with infertility treatments and advanced maternal age.Â  Monozygotic gestations are genetically identical, and can be dichorionic diamniotic, monochorionic diamniotic, or monochorionic monoamniotic depending on the time at which the division of the fertilized ovum occurs. Monochorionic diamniotic twin gestations are at risk for twin-twin transfusion syndrome and monochorionic monoamniotic gestations are at risk for conjoining or cord entanglement. (Cunningham et al., 2010)</p><h4>Diagnosis</h4><p>Â Â Â  With the common utilization of ultrasound in modern obstetrics, the diagnosis of twins is frequently made at the time of the first ultrasound. Chorionicity must be established in all twin gestations and can be most effectively determined at the first sonogram done early in the pregnancy. Findings that indicate dichorionic twins include visualization of two placental disks, dividing membrane that is &gt;2mm thick or has 3-4 layers, visualization of the twin peak or lambda sign (triangular projection of the placenta between the layers of the dividing membrane), and discordant genders. (Cunningham et al., 2010)Monochorionic twins should be referred to a Maternal Fetal Medicine specialist for consultation and management.</p><h4>Management</h4><p>Â Â Â  Prenatal care provided to women with twin pregnancies should follow APEC Guidelines for Routine Prenatal Care with the incorporation of the specific management and interpretation guidelines listed below.</p><h4>Frequency of visits</h4><ul><li>Dichorionic twin gestations should be seen every 3-4 weeks for routine care beginning at 16 weeks; conduct ultrasound surveillance of growth at 3-4 week intervals beginning at 18-20 weeks.</li><li>Monochorionic twin gestations should be followed at 2-3 week intervals; conduct ultrasound surveillance of growth at 2-3 week intervals beginning by 16 weeks with careful attention to signs of twin-twin transfusion syndrome.</li></ul><h4>Prenatal diagnosis</h4><p>Â Â Â  First and second trimester markers for aneuploidy screening are approximately twice as high in twin pregnancies as in singleton pregnancies, making it difficult to determine which fetus is responsible for an abnormal analyte concentration, however, serum screening can be performed to estimate risk. Nuchal translucency measurement of each fetus is a reasonable alternative for aneuploidy screening in multiple gestations.(D\'Alton M. E. , 2010) </p><p>Â Â Â  Maternal serum alpha-fetoprotein levels are approximately double in twins compared to singletons. A level greater than 4.0 MoM should be referred for a targeted scan to assess for neural tube and ventral wall defects. (D\'Alton M. E. , 2010) Since monochorionic twins have an increased risk of congenital anomalies, a targeted ultrasound is recommended regardless of any other screening test results.</p><h4>Medications and nutritional requirements</h4><p>Â Â Â  Women with multiple gestations have additional requirements for calories, protein, minerals, vitamins, and essential fatty acids. Consumption of energy sources should in general be 3000 Kcal/day. Weight gain recommendations for twin pregnancies are based on pre-pregnancy BMI as listed in the table below.(Luke B., 2011)</p><table style=\"width: 645px; height: 99px;\" border=\"0\"><tbody><tr><td><strong>Pre-pregnancy BMI</strong></td><td><strong>Overall wt gain at 20 wks</strong></td><td><strong>Overall wt gain at 28 wks</strong></td><td><strong>Overall wt gain at 38 wks</strong></td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>â‰¤19</strong></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\">25-35</td><td style=\"text-align: center;\">37-51</td><td style=\"text-align: center;\">50-66</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>20-24</strong></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\">20-30</td><td style=\"text-align: center;\">30-46</td><td style=\"text-align: center;\">40-56</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>25-29</strong></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\">20-25</td><td style=\"text-align: center;\">28-37</td><td style=\"text-align: center;\">38-47</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>â‰¥30</strong></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\">15-20</td><td style=\"text-align: center;\">23-28</td><td style=\"text-align: center;\">31-36</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Â Â Â Â  Given the increased risk for severe anemia due to Fe and Folate deficiency, supplementation with 60-100 mg/day of elemental iron (ferrous sulfate 325 mg/day) and 1 mg/day of folic acid is recommended with potentially greater amounts of Fe with documented anemia. (Luke B., 2011)</p><h4>Preterm birth prevention</h4><p>Â Â Â  Fifty percent of twin gestations are associated with preterm birth &lt; 37 weeks gestation with an average gestational age at delivery of 35.3 weeks. A transvaginal ultrasound cervical length of &lt;25 mm at 24 weeks is associated with an increased risk of preterm delivery before 32 weeks, however, there is no evidence that prophylactic cervical cerclage, bed rest, outpatient uterine monitoring, or long term use of prophylactic tocolytic agents is effective in preventing preterm labor or prolonging pregnancy in multiple gestations. (ACOG, 2004 reaffirmed 2009)Similarly, IM progesterone has not been found to decrease the preterm birth rate in twin gestation. (Rouse et al., 2007) Tocolytic use in twin pregnancies, in particular, has not been found to enhance gestational age at birth, birth weight, or to decrease neonatal mortality. More importantly, risks associated with tocolytics are amplified in multiple gestations and should be used judiciously. (ACOG, 2004 reaffirmed 2009) Given the lack of effective interventions for preterm birth prevention, routine cervical length screening is currently NOT recommended, but can be considered depending on the individual patient history.</p><h3>Preeclampsia</h3><p>Â Â Â  The incidence of preeclampsia is 2.6 times higher in twin gestations than singletons, therefore each clinic visit should include screening for signs and symptoms of hypertensive disease. (ACOG, 2004 reaffirmed 2009)If severe preeclampsia or HELLP syndrome develops before term, consider transfer to a tertiary care center.</p><h4>Recommendations</h4><ul><li>For monochorionic twin gestations, due to the increased risk of twin-twin transfusion syndrome, serial ultrasounds for fluid and growth should be started by no later than 16 weeks gestation and be repeated every 2-3 weeks. In addition, a targeted ultrasound and consultation with a MFM specialist should be obtained. In any case in which a monochorionic monoamniotic gestations is suspected, MFM consultation should be sought as soon as possible.</li><li>For dichorionic diamniotic twins, serial ultrasounds should be performed at 3-4 week intervals beginning at 18-20 weeks to assess for IUGR and discordance in twin pairs. Estimated fetal weights that differ &gt;20% are likely to be discordant and may require management adjustment and consultation with a MFM specialist.</li><li>Based on ACOG committee opinion endorsed by the SMFM, there is insufficient evidence to recommend any specific treatment for women with a short cervix with multiple gestations. If a short cervix is identified, consultation with a MFM specialist is recommended.</li><li>Although cessation of work with home rest has historically been recommended, there is no evidence that it prolongs pregnancy or prevents preterm birth.Â </li><li>Prophylactic cerclage is <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>not</strong> </span>recommended since it has not been shown to prolong gestation and in one meta-analysis it was found to be associated with worse outcomes. (Berghella, Odibo, To, Rust, &amp; Althuisius, 2005)</li><li>Weekly progesterone injections are <strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">not</span></strong> effective in preventing preterm birth in women with twins and should not be utilized.Â  (Rouse et al., 2007)</li><li>Provide nutrition education for 3000 Kcal/day and supplement diet with 60-100 mg/day of elemental iron (ferrous sulfate 325 mg/day) and 1 mg/day of folic acid.</li><li>Since several studies have noted an increased stillbirth rate in twin pairs in the third trimester, antenatal testing should be initiated for all twins by 32 weeks or earlier for discordant growth or other conditions (IUGR).</li><li>The National Institutes of Health recommends that women in preterm labor who have no contraindications to steroid use be given one course of steroids regardless of the number of fetuses. (ACOG, 2004 reaffirmed 2009)</li><li>Tocolytics should be used judiciously in twin pregnancies due to associated maternal and fetal risks.</li></ul><h3>Delivery</h3><p>Â Â Â  Due to the increased risk of perinatal mortality, delivery at 38 weeks, (no later than 39 weeks) in dichorionic twins should be considered as long as the pregnancy remains uncomplicated.Â  Uncomplicated monochorionic twins should be delivered at 37-38 weeks. Delivery plans should be individualized for those with complicated twin pregnancy. </p><p>Â Â Â  Several factors should be considered when determining the route of delivery for a patient with a twin pregnancy including gestational age, EFW, fetal presentation, and availability of an obstetric provider skilled in breech delivery. For twins that are vertex/vertex, it is reasonable to plan for a vaginal delivery. Vertex/non-vertex route of delivery should be determined by EFW and provider experience. If the first twin is presenting vertex, it is reasonable to offer a trial of vaginal birth. If the second twin is non-vertex, a breech extraction can be considered if:</p><ul><li>A provider experienced in breech delivery is present</li><li>EFW is â‰¥ 1500 grams</li><li>Inter-twin EFW discordance is &lt;20%</li></ul><p>Non-vertex/vertex or non-vertex/non-vertex should be delivered by cesarean section. <br />Decision to offer cesarean delivery should be individualized.</p><h4>Quality Indicators/Benchmarks</h4><ul><li>Delivery at appropriate facility</li><li>Antenatal corticosteroids preterm if labor &lt; 34 weeks</li></ul><h3 style=\"text-align: center;\">References</h3><p>ACOG. (2004 reaffirmed 2009). Multiple Gestation: Complicated Twin, Triplet, and High-Order Multifetal Pregnancy. [Practice Bulletin number 56]. Obstet Gynecol, 106, 869-883.</p><p>Berghella, V., Odibo, A. O., To, M. S., Rust, O. A., &amp; Althuisius, S. M. (2005). Cerclage for short cervix on ultrasonography: meta-analysis of trials using individual patient-level data. Obstet Gynecol, 106(1), 181-189. doi: 10.1097/01.AOG.0000168435.17200.53</p><p>Cunningham, F. G., Leveno, K. J., Bloom, S. L., Hauth, J. C., Rouse, D. J., &amp; Spong, C. Y. (2010). Williams Obstetrics (23rd ed.). New York, USA: McGraw-Hill.</p><p>D\'Alton M. E. , F. K. M. (2010). Twins, Triplets and Beyond. In J. T. Queenan, J. C. Hobbins &amp; C. Y. Spong (Eds.), Protocols for High-Risk Pregnancies (5th ed., pp. 535-544). West Sussex, UK: Wiley Blackwell.</p><p>Luke B., E. T. (2011). When you\'re expecting twins, triplets, or quads (3rd ed.). New York: Harper Collins.</p><p>Rouse, D. J., Caritis, S. N., Peaceman, A. M., Sciscione, A., Thom, E. A., Spong, C. Y., . . . Human Development Maternal-Fetal Medicine Units, N. (2007). A trial of 17 alpha-hydroxyprogesterone caproate to prevent prematurity in twins. N Engl J Med, 357(5), 454-461. doi: 10.1056/NEJMoa070641</p>'),(653,742,'section_one_label','Mtg'),(654,742,'sectionone','<h4 style=\"text-align: center;\">Management</h4><p><strong>Establish chorionicity at initial ultrasound</strong></p><p><strong>Dichorionic twin gestations:</strong></p><ul><li>Routine prenatal care visits every 3-4 weeks starting at 16 weeks gestation.</li><li>Ultrasound for growth every 3-4 weeks beginning at 18-20 weeks gestation.</li><li>Initiate antenatal testing for all twins by 32 weeks or earlier for discordant growth or other conditions (IUGR).</li><li>Delivery at 38 weeks (no later than 39 weeks) in uncomplicated pregnancies. Individualize delivery plans for complicated pregnancies.</li></ul><p><strong>Monochorionic twin gestations:</strong></p><ul><li>Routine prenatal care every 2-3 weeks.</li><li>Ultrasound for growth every 2-3 weeks beginning at 16 weeks.</li><li>Watch for signs of twin-twin transfusion syndrome.</li><li>Refer for targeted ultrasound.</li><li>Initiate antenatal testing for all twins by 32 weeks or earlier for discordant growth or other conditions (IUGR).</li><li>Delivery at 37-38 weeks for uncomplicated pregnancies. Individualize delivery plans for complicated pregnancies.</li></ul>'),(655,742,'section_two_label','Prenatal Dx'),(656,742,'sectiontwo','<h4 style=\"text-align: center;\">Prenatal Diagnosis</h4><ul><li>Markers for aneuploidy screening are approximately twice as high in twin pregnancies as in singleton pregnancies.</li><li>Maternal serum AFP levels &gt; 4.0 MoM should be referred for targeted scan.</li><li>Refer all monochorionic twin gestations for targeted scan.</li></ul>'),(657,742,'section_three_label','Rec'),(658,742,'sectionthree','<h4 style=\"text-align: center;\">Recommendations</h4><ul><li>Provide nutritional education for 3000 Kcal/day.</li><li>Supplement diet with 60-100 mg/day elemental iron (ferrous sulfate 325 mg/day) and 1 mg/day folic acid.</li><li>Prophylactic cerclage is not recommended; consult with MFM specialist for short cervix.</li><li>Progesterone is not effective in preventing preterm birth twin pregnancies and should not be used.</li><li>Although cessation of work with home rest has historically been recommended, there is no evidence that it prolongs pregnancy or prevents preterm birth.</li><li>In the event of preterm labor, use tocolytics judiciously due to associated maternal and fetal risks.</li><li>Women in preterm labor should be given one course of steroids regardless of the number of fetuses.</li><li>Route of delivery depends on gestational age, EFW, fetal presentation, and obstetric providerâ€™s skill in breech deliveries.</li></ul><table style=\"width: 645px; height: 99px;\" border=\"0\"><tbody><tr><td><strong>Pre-pregnancy BMI</strong></td><td><strong>Overall wt gain at 20 wks</strong></td><td><strong>Overall wt gain at 28 wks</strong></td><td><strong>Overall wt gain at 38 wks</strong></td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>â‰¤19</strong></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\">25-35</td><td style=\"text-align: center;\">37-51</td><td style=\"text-align: center;\">50-66</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>20-24</strong></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\">20-30</td><td style=\"text-align: center;\">30-46</td><td style=\"text-align: center;\">40-56</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>25-29</strong></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\">20-25</td><td style=\"text-align: center;\">28-37</td><td style=\"text-align: center;\">38-47</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>â‰¥30</strong></td><td style=\"text-align: center;\">15-20</td><td style=\"text-align: center;\">23-28</td><td style=\"text-align: center;\">31-36</td></tr></tbody></table>'),(659,742,'section_four_label','QI'),(660,742,'sectionfour','<h4 style=\"text-align: left;\">Quality Indicators/Benchmarks</h4><p>&nbsp;</p><ul><li>Delivery at appropriate facility</li><li>Antenatal corticosteroids preterm if labor &lt; 34 weeks</li></ul>'),(661,742,'section_five_label',''),(662,742,'sectionfive',''),(663,742,'version','01/08/2014'),(664,742,'description',''),(516,405,'section_one_label','Screen'),(517,405,'sectionone','<h3>Initial Visit</h3><p>Â Â Â  Screen <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>all</strong></span> pregnant women for ASB with a clean-catch, mid-stream urine for culture and sensitivity at their initial prenatal visit. If the culture comes back contaminated, repeat by mini-cath.</p><h4>Repeat Cultures*</h4><p>Needed each trimester in patients with:</p><ul><li>Sickle cell disease or trait</li><li>Insulin dependent diabetes</li><li>Autoimmune disease</li></ul><p>*Clean catch, mid-stream urine; if contaminated, repeat by mini-cath.</p>'),(518,405,'section_two_label','Cystitis'),(519,405,'sectiontwo','<h3>Cystitis</h3><ul><li>Diagnose by history and examination of un-spun mini-cath urine for evidence of WBCs or bacteria.</li><li>Confirm with culture and sensitivity.</li><li>As an alternative to microscopy: urine dip with leukocyte esterase and nitrite can be utilized to diagnose infection in the setting of suggestive symptoms.</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>'),(520,405,'section_three_label','Mtg'),(521,405,'sectionthree','<h3>Management</h3><h4>Culture positive</h4><p>Nitrofurantoin 100mg two times per day for 3 days</p><p><strong>OR</strong></p><p>If not sulfa allergic andÂ  beyond the first trimester but &lt; 34 weeks: Trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole (Bactrim DS) 160/100mg twice a day for 3 days</p><h4>Repeat urine culture and sensitivity 7-10 days after treatment</h4><ul><li>An increasing number of organisms are developing antibiotic resistance, culture and sensitivity is more important than in the past in order to ensure the patient is receiving appropriate therapy.</li><li>If Urine culture continues to be positive, check compliance and bacteria sensitivity and re-treat</li><li>Women with repeat positive urine culture may be treated with chronic antibiotic suppression such as Nitrofurantoin 100mg at bedtime</li></ul><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>'),(522,405,'section_four_label','Pyelo'),(523,405,'sectionfour','<h3>Acute Pyelonephritis</h3><ol><li>Hospitalize patient.</li><li>Obtain urine culture. If patient appears significantly ill, obtain blood cultures as well as these may be positive prior to the urine culture.</li><li>Evaluate CBC, serum creatinine, and electrolytes.</li><li>Administer IV hydration to ensure adequate urinary output and replete any electrolyte disturbances.</li><li>Monitor vital signs, including pulse oximetry, and urinary output frequently and strictly.</li><li>Administer intravenous antimicrobial therapy with a 3rd generation cephalosporin (e.g. ceftriaxone), a beta-lactam with good gram negative coverage (e.g. piperacillin/tazobactam) or ampicillin and gentamicin.</li><li>Obtain chest radiograph if dyspnea or tachypnea is present. If evidence of pulmonary edema or oxygen saturation &lt;95%, consider MFM or pulmonary consultation.</li><li>Repeat hematology and chemistry studies in 48 hours.</li><li>Change to oral antimicrobials when afebrile 24-48 hrs.</li><li>Discharge when afebrile 24-48 hours, provide oral antimicrobial therapy for an additional 14 days.</li><li>After completion of acute course of therapy, patient should receive suppressive therapy for the remainder of pregnancy such as Nitrofurantion 100 mg at bedtime.</li></ol>'),(524,405,'section_five_label','QI'),(525,405,'sectionfive','<h3>Quality Indicators/Benchmarks</h3><ul><li>Urine culture at initial visit</li></ul>'),(526,405,'version','5/13/2013');
